WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.380
interessante e importante, ma che può avere effetti negativi.

00:04.660 --> 00:07.520
Per i centri tecnici,

00:07.620 --> 00:11.740
abbiamo imparato il messaggio fondamentale dei centri tecnici

00:11.740 --> 00:15.680
di aiutare le proprietà ad apprendere.

00:15.860 --> 00:19.480
Ci sono dei servizi di cui le proprietà, soprattutto di piccole dimensioni,

00:19.740 --> 00:22.280
avranno bisogno, a causa della loro incapacità, di internalizzare

00:22.280 --> 00:25.160
tutte le fasi del processo produttivo o dei servizi,

00:25.400 --> 00:27.220
ma che, per l'altro, non conoscono.

00:27.220 --> 00:29.660
Questa è la funzione dei centri tecnici

00:29.660 --> 00:32.320
e è una funzione pubblica,

00:32.580 --> 00:34.860
quindi una presenza è necessaria.

00:35.220 --> 00:36.660
Il ultimo punto, e su questo concludo,

00:36.940 --> 00:38.000
sono i community colleges.

00:38.780 --> 00:41.100
Bene, il punto che mi ritengo è l'idea in se stessa,

00:41.980 --> 00:43.260
il fatto che possa esistere,

00:43.380 --> 00:45.920
deve esistere una formazione tecnica

00:45.920 --> 00:49.280
a preduzio e non necessariamente universitaria

00:49.280 --> 00:53.260
che deve essere gestita direttamente con le proprietà

00:53.260 --> 00:56.600
e, a luogo di una struttura universitaria.

00:57.540 --> 00:59.240
Bene, questi sono i punti generali

00:59.240 --> 01:01.680
che concernano tutti i membri dell'OCDE,

01:02.280 --> 01:04.840
sono i punti su cui ho trovato la mia attenzione

01:05.540 --> 01:09.660
e sono punti a complesso delle cose che la signora Odile Sallard ha detto.

01:10.060 --> 01:13.600
Vi ringrazio molto, signor Presidente.

01:23.460 --> 01:27.200
Signor Presidente, voglio dire che siamo a conclusione

01:27.200 --> 01:28.860
di due giornate di lavoro

01:28.860 --> 01:32.940
che hanno beneficiato di tutto quello che sa offrire

01:32.940 --> 01:34.940
una città come Modena,

01:35.220 --> 01:38.820
una città di grande storia, leggiadra e nobile

01:38.820 --> 01:42.720
e che ha favorito la discussione tra i più grandi esperti

01:42.720 --> 01:43.580
dell'OXE, dell'Occident, dell'Occident, dell'Occident,

01:43.580 --> 01:46.600
e di paesi delegati di vari paesi

01:46.600 --> 01:49.280
che hanno partecipato a queste due giornate di lavoro.

01:50.420 --> 01:52.880
Quello che è importante è che l'Italia

01:52.880 --> 01:55.980
in qualche modo si fa sostenitrice

01:55.980 --> 01:58.480
di questa istituzione dell'OXE, come lei l'ha detto

01:58.480 --> 02:02.400
quando ha incontrato il segretario generale Johnston lo scorso anno,

02:03.620 --> 02:06.580
e anzi ha ribadito certi punti forza,

02:06.980 --> 02:09.820
azioni propositive nel programma dell'OXE.

02:09.820 --> 02:15.160
E sono lieto ora di dare la parola al decano

02:15.420 --> 02:17.840
dei segretari generali dell'OXE,

02:18.280 --> 02:21.440
il vero Dean, malgrado la giovane età,

02:21.700 --> 02:25.600
Joanna Shelton, che viene in qualche modo a dirle

02:25.600 --> 02:30.600
quello che è il consensus del Consiglio Ministerale

02:30.600 --> 02:34.060
che si è appena svolto qualche settimana or sono a Parigi

02:34.480 --> 02:37.560
e dirle quelle che sono le preoccupazioni dell'istituzione

02:37.560 --> 02:42.560
in quanto tale, in modo da poter ascoltare lei Presidente

02:43.300 --> 02:47.720
e portare al Consiglio dei Paesi membri le sue preoccupazioni.

02:48.300 --> 02:53.040
Quindi, se me lo consente, prego il segretario generale aggiunto,

02:53.220 --> 02:56.800
Joanna Shelton, di darci il suo messaggio.

03:07.560 --> 03:12.220
Mr. Prime Minister, Mr. Ambassador, Mr. Mayor,

03:13.300 --> 03:15.700
other distinguished guests and ladies and gentlemen,

03:16.740 --> 03:19.580
I am truly very honored to be with you here today

03:19.580 --> 03:23.340
in the historic and economically important city of Modena

03:23.340 --> 03:25.920
in the region of Emilia Romagna.

03:27.480 --> 03:30.100
The OECD greatly appreciates the opportunity

03:30.100 --> 03:34.220
to cooperate with the city of Modena in holding this conference

03:34.220 --> 03:37.980
to discuss the many important questions related to building

03:37.980 --> 03:40.040
competitive regional economies.

03:41.820 --> 03:45.420
Modena and Emilia Romagna are well known

03:45.420 --> 03:48.620
for their Roman antiquities and cultural amenities,

03:48.620 --> 03:50.960
and I should add for their excellent food,

03:51.020 --> 03:53.380
which I tested today and last evening,

03:54.500 --> 03:58.640
but they are equally well known for their agricultural specialties

03:58.640 --> 04:00.600
and industrial prowess.

04:00.600 --> 04:04.520
They provide a good example of the important linkages

04:04.520 --> 04:08.600
that exist between local and regional economies on the one hand

04:08.600 --> 04:12.760
and national and international economies on the other.

04:13.860 --> 04:18.100
Our work at the OECD and the work of this conference

04:18.100 --> 04:22.820
make it clear that government policies at all levels

04:22.820 --> 04:26.040
must take into account a wide range of factors

04:26.040 --> 04:30.320
that together affect the economic viability

04:30.320 --> 04:34.240
and competitiveness of cities, regions and nations.

04:35.920 --> 04:38.980
You have focused in depth for two days on the challenges

04:38.980 --> 04:41.840
entailed in crafting effective regional policies

04:41.840 --> 04:45.860
and the experiences of OECD member countries in that regard.

04:47.060 --> 04:50.860
I would like to take a step back and give you my perspective

04:50.860 --> 04:53.840
on how those regional policies are intimately linked

04:53.840 --> 04:57.040
with policies at the national and international level.

04:58.200 --> 05:01.700
I will do so by describing some of our activities at the OECD

05:01.700 --> 05:05.200
and the views of our ministers as recently expressed

05:05.200 --> 05:07.260
at our annual meeting of ministers.

05:09.600 --> 05:14.400
OECD ministers, during their annual meeting in April in Paris,

05:15.480 --> 05:18.220
focused their attention on a range of issues of concern

05:18.220 --> 05:20.300
on the international economic scene.

05:20.300 --> 05:24.820
Among them was the recent economic crisis in Asia

05:24.820 --> 05:28.240
and its implications for the countries directly affected

05:28.240 --> 05:30.820
and for OECD countries.

05:31.940 --> 05:34.820
Ministers noted that the crisis has highlighted

05:34.820 --> 05:38.320
the growing interdependence of countries in the world economy

05:38.320 --> 05:42.740
as well as the importance of having well-functioning markets

05:42.740 --> 05:46.440
and efficient economies and supportive mechanisms

05:46.440 --> 05:48.520
of international cooperation.

05:48.520 --> 05:53.880
Stable macroeconomic policies backed by sound

05:53.880 --> 05:57.460
and transparent public finances and control of inflation

05:57.460 --> 06:00.680
are an indispensable part of the equation.

06:02.720 --> 06:05.740
Of equal importance, both to countries in Asia

06:05.740 --> 06:08.640
and to countries in the OECD and elsewhere,

06:09.540 --> 06:13.970
is good public governance and effective structural policies

06:13.970 --> 06:18.170
relating to financial systems, regulatory reform,

06:19.090 --> 06:22.370
corporate governance and labor and product markets.

06:23.630 --> 06:27.310
Finally, ministers agreed that it is important

06:27.310 --> 06:30.890
that all countries maintain open markets for trade

06:30.890 --> 06:34.290
and investment so that the benefits of participation

06:34.290 --> 06:36.910
in a global economy can be realized.

06:38.730 --> 06:42.390
This latter point relates to an issue that ministers discussed

06:42.390 --> 06:45.890
at length during their annual meeting, and that is

06:45.890 --> 06:49.790
how to respond to the challenges which globalization presents

06:49.790 --> 06:52.510
for OECD members and non-members alike.

06:53.470 --> 06:57.490
The world is growing smaller and nations and regions

06:57.490 --> 07:01.070
are more closely linked than ever before in history.

07:02.130 --> 07:05.130
This is due to the significant reduction in trade

07:05.130 --> 07:07.670
and investment barriers in the post-war period

07:07.670 --> 07:11.390
as well as to the revolution in transportation

07:11.390 --> 07:13.350
and communications technology.

07:14.950 --> 07:17.770
Today, the volume of world trade in goods

07:17.770 --> 07:22.410
is about 16 times its level in 1950.

07:23.610 --> 07:26.410
Foreign direct investment outflows have increased

07:26.410 --> 07:32.730
even more rapidly, rising 25-fold in the past 25 years

07:32.730 --> 07:38.710
from $14 billion to $350 billion annually.

07:40.450 --> 07:42.550
Increasing numbers of countries are involved in

07:42.550 --> 07:45.370
and benefiting from the dynamics of globalization.

07:46.490 --> 07:49.790
The latest World Development Report of the World Bank

07:49.790 --> 07:54.070
has reported that world poverty has been reduced more

07:54.070 --> 07:59.750
in the past 50 years than at any time in the past 500 years.

08:00.810 --> 08:03.050
This is no accident.

08:04.130 --> 08:07.830
More countries around the world have come to understand

08:07.830 --> 08:12.630
that go-it-alone or protectionist strategies do not work.

08:13.790 --> 08:17.150
They have come to realize that participation in the global economy

08:17.290 --> 08:22.370
brings ideas, competition and growth to home markets

08:22.370 --> 08:26.490
and provides an outlet for creative local entrepreneurs.

08:27.490 --> 08:30.930
Yet the phenomenon that is known as globalization

08:31.490 --> 08:34.910
also means change in economies and societies.

08:36.250 --> 08:39.510
Issues which until recently were solely or primarily

08:39.510 --> 08:43.670
of domestic concern, such as taxation, regulation

08:43.670 --> 08:48.630
or even environmental policy, increasingly have implications

08:48.630 --> 08:50.730
that carry beyond national borders.

08:51.670 --> 08:55.950
As a result, there are constituencies in all parts of the world

08:55.950 --> 08:59.830
who fear or resist the changes brought about

08:59.830 --> 09:02.010
by globalization and technology.

09:03.050 --> 09:05.430
This is an area where government action

09:05.550 --> 09:08.670
and open public debate is critical.

09:10.710 --> 09:15.110
At their April meeting, OECD ministers addressed these concerns,

09:15.730 --> 09:18.330
drawing on a recent OECD study entitled

09:18.790 --> 09:22.230
Open Markets Matter, the Benefits of Trade

09:22.230 --> 09:23.650
and Investment Liberalization.

09:24.490 --> 09:28.590
That study examines the experience of member countries

09:28.590 --> 09:32.090
in the post-war period up to and including

09:32.090 --> 09:35.850
the Uruguay Round, the North American Free Trade Agreement

09:35.850 --> 09:41.010
and the European Single Market, and demonstrates the clear net benefits

09:41.010 --> 09:43.810
for economic growth, employment and prosperity

09:44.210 --> 09:47.230
brought about by trade and investment liberalization.

09:48.490 --> 09:51.710
The study also deals with the growing public concerns

09:51.710 --> 09:55.030
on social, labor and environmental issues

09:55.030 --> 09:57.730
and shows that liberalization

09:57.730 --> 10:14.910
is not the most important cause of transformation

10:14.910 --> 10:17.090
in our economies and societies.

10:17.090 --> 10:20.410
Many other factors are in play,

10:20.830 --> 10:24.390
most notably technology-driven structural change.

10:25.290 --> 10:30.430
Moreover, protection is not the answer to these social concerns.

10:31.250 --> 10:35.690
What is needed are policies targeted to the root of the problem,

10:36.210 --> 10:38.190
and that is where the work of this conference

10:38.190 --> 10:42.790
on regional development policies and work in other parts of the OECD

10:42.790 --> 10:44.090
is so important.

10:45.530 --> 10:48.270
Before addressing the question of regional policies,

10:48.790 --> 10:52.570
I'd like to outline briefly some of the ways in which the OECD is working

10:52.570 --> 10:55.830
to maintain and improve the capacity of economies

10:55.830 --> 10:58.110
to grow and adapt to change.

10:59.610 --> 11:03.510
The mission of the OECD is to promote economic growth

11:03.510 --> 11:06.470
and development in member and non-member countries

11:06.470 --> 11:11.230
and to contribute to an open international trade and investment system.

11:11.230 --> 11:15.170
We engage policy makers such as yourselves

11:15.170 --> 11:19.290
from member countries on a range of issues of common concern

11:19.290 --> 11:23.090
across virtually all major economic and social disciplines,

11:23.090 --> 11:28.270
and we work together to develop appropriate policy responses.

11:29.530 --> 11:33.030
Some examples include the OECD jobs strategy,

11:33.970 --> 11:37.230
the OECD recommendations on regulatory reform,

11:37.230 --> 11:41.370
and our current priority work on corporate governance

11:41.370 --> 11:45.070
and the challenges posed by electronic commerce.

11:47.070 --> 11:52.150
In some policy areas, our members enter into legally binding commitments,

11:52.750 --> 11:56.330
such as the convention prohibiting bribery and corruption

11:56.330 --> 12:00.530
of foreign public officials signed by ministers last December.

12:01.790 --> 12:06.630
Another example is the Multilateral Agreement on Investment, or MAI,

12:06.630 --> 12:10.350
currently being negotiated by OECD countries

12:10.350 --> 12:13.870
and an important number of non-OECD countries.

12:15.350 --> 12:18.050
International investment has become increasingly important

12:18.230 --> 12:21.250
as a vehicle for economic growth and integration.

12:22.210 --> 12:27.330
Yet unlike trade, the multilateral system lacks a framework for investment.

12:28.610 --> 12:33.810
The MAI will provide a comprehensive and stable framework for investment,

12:33.810 --> 12:39.950
guaranteeing non-discriminatory treatment for foreign and domestic investors

12:39.950 --> 12:44.070
in signatory countries and a means of settling disputes.

12:45.170 --> 12:49.410
Once completed, and I remain very optimistic that it will be,

12:50.090 --> 12:55.550
the MAI will give new impetus to growth, employment and living standards.

12:56.430 --> 13:02.290
If signed by Asian crisis countries, the MAI would send a very positive signal

13:02.290 --> 13:05.910
to foreign investors about the investment climate in those countries.

13:07.410 --> 13:10.530
Now the issues I've touched on above may seem far removed

13:10.530 --> 13:13.930
from your preoccupations at the conference over the past two days.

13:15.090 --> 13:18.730
I would suggest they are not. They are complementary.

13:20.190 --> 13:24.510
Building and sustaining economic growth at the local and regional level

13:24.510 --> 13:28.170
requires a solid architecture for the global economy

13:28.170 --> 13:31.230
with fair and transparent rules for all.

13:32.450 --> 13:37.310
As so many of your examples show, small and medium-sized firms

13:37.310 --> 13:41.530
are active not only in the local or regional economy,

13:42.310 --> 13:46.830
they also are increasingly important players in international markets.

13:48.070 --> 13:53.090
Small and medium-sized firms, which are so important to Italy and this region,

13:53.090 --> 13:57.890
will benefit most from a successful multilateral agreement on investment

13:57.890 --> 14:01.650
since large multinational firms already have access

14:01.650 --> 14:03.990
to numerous markets through investment.

14:06.230 --> 14:09.470
There is a clear complementarity between the challenges

14:09.470 --> 14:11.670
of international economic performance

14:11.670 --> 14:15.090
and the challenges of regional economic development.

14:16.090 --> 14:19.330
None of us can overlook the fact that protectionist pressures

14:19.330 --> 14:22.470
against continued trade and investment liberalization

14:22.470 --> 14:25.990
are most acute in those areas and regions

14:25.990 --> 14:29.310
which fail to create their own economic dynamism.

14:30.250 --> 14:33.870
This brings me to the importance of regional development policies.

14:38.690 --> 14:43.330
At their meeting in Paris, OECD ministers expressed their concern

14:43.330 --> 14:46.210
over the persistence of employment and income disparities

14:46.210 --> 14:50.690
between different regions even in countries enjoying rapid economic growth.

14:51.830 --> 14:54.690
These disparities threaten national cohesion

14:55.030 --> 14:58.350
and also undermine overall economic performance

14:58.350 --> 15:01.010
by weakening links between regions

15:01.010 --> 15:05.270
and generating spillover costs for the economy as a whole.

15:06.630 --> 15:11.570
The lack of regional convergence in OECD countries is a clear sign

15:11.570 --> 15:15.210
that some areas are less able to adapt their economies

15:15.210 --> 15:17.830
to changing circumstances than others.

15:18.970 --> 15:22.750
This lack of convergence creates pressures to resist change

15:22.750 --> 15:25.090
and encourages wasteful subsidies.

15:26.470 --> 15:29.390
But national policies alone may not be sufficient

15:29.390 --> 15:31.330
to address these regional disparities.

15:32.110 --> 15:36.330
It seems clear that in some cases, traditional policy responses

15:36.330 --> 15:39.250
must be complemented with more targeted approaches.

15:40.250 --> 15:45.010
Regional policy, combined with appropriately designed structural policies,

15:45.630 --> 15:48.530
are one possible way to address this challenge.

15:50.730 --> 15:53.190
This conference has explored many of the elements

15:53.190 --> 15:57.030
that are necessary components of a successful regional development strategy

15:57.030 --> 15:59.890
and has outlined areas for future work.

16:00.910 --> 16:05.930
There are numerous examples of small towns and rural areas in OECD countries

16:05.930 --> 16:10.290
whose relatively underdeveloped economies following World War II

16:10.290 --> 16:14.150
were transformed into prosperous industrial centers

16:14.150 --> 16:17.370
in a surprisingly short period of time.

16:18.170 --> 16:22.170
The experience of the industrial districts in the Emilia-Romagna region

16:22.170 --> 16:23.610
are among the best known.

16:25.190 --> 16:29.250
A major element in the success of the Emilia-Romagna region

16:29.750 --> 16:33.690
appears to have been the ability to incorporate new ideas

16:33.690 --> 16:38.490
and to innovate on the foundation of a highly skilled labor force.

16:39.270 --> 16:43.970
This did not require expensive research and development or product development.

16:44.890 --> 16:48.830
Rather, it was the result of incremental innovation

16:48.830 --> 16:54.230
and a highly efficient transfer of knowledge and technology within the area.

16:55.250 --> 16:58.850
This experience confirms the experience of other countries

16:58.850 --> 17:03.950
where past policies relying on financial and fiscal incentives

17:03.950 --> 17:09.010
for regional development have proved to be controversial, costly,

17:09.810 --> 17:15.650
and, despite some success stories, not highly effective over the long term.

17:16.630 --> 17:19.810
Governments increasingly are seeking regional policy approaches

17:19.810 --> 17:22.550
with clearer developmental objectives

17:22.550 --> 17:27.110
and which develop and harness local resources and capacities.

17:27.110 --> 17:30.770
Yet, countries' experience in this area is limited.

17:32.170 --> 17:38.010
The challenge for you as policymakers and experts in the field is twofold.

17:38.890 --> 17:42.970
First, to try to improve our understanding of the factors

17:42.970 --> 17:45.330
that affect regional economic competitiveness,

17:46.050 --> 17:50.290
and second, to work to elaborate best practices in this area

17:50.290 --> 17:52.230
in order to guide future policy.

17:52.230 --> 17:58.990
The challenge is also to draw upon and integrate your work with

17:58.990 --> 18:03.070
that taking place at a national and international level in other disciplines,

18:03.530 --> 18:07.870
such as labor markets, human capital development, and entrepreneurship.

18:09.010 --> 18:12.710
We at the OECD are prepared to contribute our expertise to this effort.

18:13.270 --> 18:17.630
Indeed, this conference is one example of the types of cooperative approaches

18:17.630 --> 18:21.190
that can be pursued with experts from governments, think tanks,

18:21.190 --> 18:23.590
academia, and the private sector.

18:25.850 --> 18:28.890
The global economy offers immense opportunities.

18:30.010 --> 18:33.410
Successfully mastered, it holds out the most promising opportunity

18:33.750 --> 18:37.450
to contribute to a continued increase in the living standards

18:37.450 --> 18:39.530
of citizens of all countries.

18:40.570 --> 18:44.210
But globalization is not a process which is free of risks.

18:45.110 --> 18:49.790
It increasingly requires governments to learn from each other's policy successes

18:49.790 --> 18:54.390
and failures, and to cooperate in fashioning policy responses

18:54.390 --> 18:57.710
to the common challenges faced by all countries.

18:58.930 --> 19:02.790
The important lessons learned from Italy's experience in regional development,

19:03.430 --> 19:07.710
as well as the experience of other countries, should be put to good use

19:07.710 --> 19:11.430
in helping all governments prepare their economies and societies

19:11.430 --> 19:13.250
for a world of the future.

19:13.250 --> 19:19.570
Mr. Prime Minister, Mr. Ambassador, Mr. Mayor, ladies and gentlemen,

19:19.950 --> 19:23.670
I thank you once again for the great pleasure and honor of joining you

19:23.670 --> 19:26.450
in the beautiful city of Modena to discuss these issues,

19:26.690 --> 19:29.710
and I look forward to continued cooperation with you in the future.

19:29.890 --> 19:30.870
Thank you.

19:40.810 --> 19:44.930
Presidente, prima di darle la parola, vorrei che il primo cittadino di questa città,

19:45.670 --> 19:49.870
il sindaco Giuliano Barbolini, che ci ha accolto con tanta generosità,

19:51.270 --> 19:54.190
dica delle parole di giusta presentazione.

19:55.250 --> 19:56.210
Grazie.

19:57.050 --> 20:00.930
Rapidissimamente, io esprimo una soddisfazione,

20:01.750 --> 20:07.650
perché lo svolgimento di questi due giorni di discussione

20:07.650 --> 20:11.150
ha corrisposto almeno alle nostre aspirazioni e attese.

20:12.010 --> 20:16.150
Noi siamo una realtà che ha conosciuto e conosce

20:17.190 --> 20:21.570
una dinamica di sviluppo particolarmente qualificato,

20:21.570 --> 20:24.690
così come è caratteristica di questa regione,

20:24.870 --> 20:28.730
e credo che questa potenzialità positiva

20:29.370 --> 20:32.470
è stata anche riconosciuta autorevolmente dall'OXE

20:33.450 --> 20:39.650
come un laboratorio interessante sul quale stabilire delle relazioni

20:39.650 --> 20:44.250
e da mettere in rete con altre esperienze e situazioni.

20:44.930 --> 20:47.070
Nonostante questi elementi di positività,

20:47.330 --> 20:50.890
però noi ci misuriamo anche come sfide di un mondo che cambia

20:50.890 --> 20:55.290
e quindi con la necessità che è il tessuto delle piccole e medie imprese,

20:55.450 --> 20:58.330
che questa dimensione territoriale riesca

20:58.330 --> 21:01.310
a esprimere una maggiore capacità sistemica

21:01.310 --> 21:04.750
per competere meglio come territorio nel suo insieme,

21:06.130 --> 21:09.370
sapendo far diavogare le istituzioni,

21:09.610 --> 21:13.370
l'agire dei soggetti privati, imprenditoriali, dei lavoratori

21:13.370 --> 21:15.190
e anche la capacità di innovazione.

21:15.890 --> 21:17.790
Il tema della capacità di innovazione

21:17.790 --> 21:22.210
e il raccordo con i luoghi dove si fa ricerca

21:22.210 --> 21:26.870
che può essere poi spesa a servizio dei processi produttivi

21:26.870 --> 21:31.690
è uno degli elementi sui quali maggiormente ci interroghiamo e cerchiamo di lavorare.

21:31.830 --> 21:34.030
Mi pare che da questa conferenza,

21:34.170 --> 21:38.790
da vindicazioni e dai suggerimenti che poi l'OXE tradurrà in direttive,

21:40.050 --> 21:43.850
possano uscire degli stimoli sicuramente utili per noi,

21:44.030 --> 21:46.870
anche perché noi abbiamo visto dalla discussione di questi giorni

21:46.870 --> 21:51.550
confermate alcune linee di lavoro sulle quali stiamo cercando di operare

21:51.550 --> 21:54.550
e mi auguro che la nostra esperienza

21:54.550 --> 21:57.290
confrontata con quella di altre realtà e situazioni

21:57.290 --> 21:59.970
possa anche concorrere ad arricchire...

